Data Story on US presidentsâ€™ inaugural speeches

The United States has experienced three major economic crises in the twentieth century. During these important economic crises, three presidents were formally inaugurated. They were Franklin Roosevelt, Ronald Reagan and Barack Obama. I choose these three presidents and the most controversial president in America history, Donald Trump, to study the similarities and differences between their inaugural speeches. Comparing the first inaugural addresses of these presidents may provide us important clues to their policies and attitudes which they have at different times.

Read the text file

folder.path="~/Desktop/Applied Data Science/wk2-TextMining//data/inaugurals/"
docs<-Corpus(DirSource(folder.path))

Cleaning the text

# Convert the text to lower case
docs <- tm_map(docs, content_transformer(tolower))
# Remove numbers
docs <- tm_map(docs, removeNumbers)
# Remove english common stopwords
docs <- tm_map(docs, removeWords, stopwords("english"))
# Remove punctuations
docs <- tm_map(docs, removePunctuation)
# Eliminate extra white spaces
docs <- tm_map(docs, stripWhitespace)

Word frequency

These are top 10 most commonly used words in the speeches.

#Build term-document matrix
tdm.1 <- TermDocumentMatrix(docs["inaugFranklinDRoosevelt-1.txt"])
m.1 <- as.matrix(tdm.1)
v.1 <- sort(rowSums(m.1),decreasing=TRUE)
d.1 <- data.frame(word = names(v.1),freq=v.1)
tdm.2 <- TermDocumentMatrix(docs["inaugRonaldReagan-1.txt"])
m.2 <- as.matrix(tdm.2)

Generate the Word cloud

The word cloud is a informative way to look at the most common words in speeches as a whole.

par(mfrow=c(1,2))
set.seed(1234)
#Franklin Roosevelt
wordcloud(words = d.1$word, freq = d.1$freq, min.freq = 2,
          max.words=100, random.order=FALSE, rot.per=0.35, 
          colors=brewer.pal(4, "Dark2"))
#Ronald Reagan
wordcloud(words = d.2$word, freq = d.2$freq, min.freq = 2,
          max.words=200, random.order=FALSE, rot.per=0.35, 
          colors=brewer.pal(4, "Dark2"))

Compare these four word clouds, we can see that the frequency of word repetition is relatively high for president Roosevelt. United States was under the worst depression and economic crisis in the history when Franklin Roosevelt became President of America for the first time. So we can see words like â€œhelpedâ€,â€œfailureâ€, â€œdarkâ€ in the word cloud. Reagan as a anti-establishment politician, different from other presidents. He thinks government is the problem, but not the solution to the problem. So he emphasizes the word â€œgovernmentâ€ in his speech. We can see that both Obama and Trump used the word â€œamericaâ€ frequently in their speeches. The words like â€œtodayâ€, â€œnowâ€, â€œtimeâ€ can somehow reveal Obamaâ€™s positive attitude to revolution. In fact, he indeed launched a series of new policies very quickly after his inauguration.

Words in common

We know that both Roosevelt and Obama are democratic presidents while Reagan and Trump are republican presidents. It can be interesting to see whether presidents from the same political party share a similar speech delivering style.

par(mfrow=c(1,2))
#Roosevelt and Obama
row.1<-rownames(m.1)
row.3<-rownames(m.3)
common.row<-intersect(row.1,row.3)
common.1<-as.matrix(m.1[common.row,])
common.3<-as.matrix(m.3[common.row,])
common.words<-cbind(common.1,common.3)
diff<-abs(common.words[,1]-common.words[,2])
common.words<-cbind(common.words,diff)
common.words<-common.words[order(common.words[,3],decreasing=TRUE),]
top25.df<-data.frame(x=common.words[1:25,1],y=common.words[1:25,2],labels=rownames(common.words[1:25,]))
#polarized tag plot
pyramid.plot(top25.df$x,top25.df$y,labels=top25.df$labels,gap=15,top.labels = c("Roosevelt","word","Obama"),main="words in common",laxlab=NULL,raxlab=NULL,unit=NULL)

[1] 4 2 4 2

The plot contains words that are in common but have the 25 largest differences in use. Except the words like â€œwillâ€, â€œcanâ€, â€œnationâ€ show in all four speeches, the words Reagon and Trump have in common are very different from what Roosevelt and Obama have. Roosevelt and Obama appeared to show a great concern in economy and work as democratic presidents. And the words like â€œbordersâ€, â€œacrossâ€ on the other hand revealed Reagan and Trumpâ€™s great concern in defense and immigration.

Length of sentences

par(mfrow=c(2,2))
#FranklinDRoosevelt
lines.1 <- readLines("~/Desktop/Applied Data Science/wk2-TextMining/data/inaugurals/inaugFranklinDRoosevelt-1.txt")
lines.1 <- strsplit(lines.1, "[.!?] *")
Roosevelt<- unlist(lines.1, use.names=FALSE)
#count words in a sentence
temp1<-numeric(length(Roosevelt))
for(i in 1:length(Roosevelt)){
  temp1[i]<-sapply(gregexpr("\\W+", Roosevelt[i]), length)
}
group1<-rep("Roosevelt",length(Roosevelt))
n1<-1:length(Roosevelt)
r1<-data.frame(n1,temp1,group1)
beeswarm(temp1, 
         data=r1,
         horizontal = FALSE, 
         pch=16, col=alpha(brewer.pal(9, "Set1"), 0.6), 
         cex=0.55, cex.axis=0.8, cex.lab=0.8,
         las=2, 
         main="Franklin Roosevelt")

In the above plots, y-axis represents the number of words in a sentence and dots with the same y value represent sentences with the same length. The plot of president Roosevelt has long and thin upper half. It shows that Roosevelt is the one who likes to use long sentences. The middle part of Reaganâ€™s plot is very wide, so most sentences he used are neither too long or too short. President Obama is famous for his eloquence, here the length of sentences in his speech is evenly distributed comparing with other three presidents. Trump is a straight talker, this might explains why he prefers very short sentences. His way of talking is more direct and practical.

sentiment analysis

Explore the emotion difference between speeches from each president with the NRC emotion lexicon. The get_nrc_sentiment function returns a data frame in which each row represents a sentence from the original file. The columns include one for each emotion type.

#FranklinDRoosevelt
d.1<-get_nrc_sentiment(Roosevelt)
td.1<-data.frame(t(d.1))
td_new.1 <- data.frame(rowSums(td.1[-1]))
#Transformation and  cleaning
names(td_new.1)[1] <- "count"
td_new.1 <- cbind("sentiment" = rownames(td_new.1), td_new.1)
rownames(td_new.1) <- NULL
td_new2.1<-td_new.1[1:8,]
#Visualisation
plot.1<-qplot(sentiment, data=td_new2.1, weight=count, geom="bar",fill=sentiment)+ggtitle("Franklin D Roosevelt")
#RonaldReagan
d.2<-get_nrc_sentiment(Reagan)
td.2<-data.frame(t(d.2))
td_new.2 <- data.frame(rowSums(td.2[-1]))
#Transformation and  cleaning
names(td_new.2)[1] <- "count"
td_new.2 <- cbind("sentiment" = rownames(td_new.2), td_new.2)
rownames(td_new.2) <- NULL
td_new2.2<-td_new.2[1:8,]
#Visualisation
plot.2<-qplot(sentiment, data=td_new2.2, weight=count, geom="bar",fill=sentiment)+ggtitle("Ronald Reagan")
grid.arrange(plot.1, plot.2,ncol=2)

NRC emotion lexicon divides emotion into eight types: anger, fear, anticipation, trust, surprise, sadness, joy, and disgust. In the plot, each bar represents how prominent each of the emotion is in text. One thing worth noticing is that although inaugurated under major economic crises, Reaganâ€™s emotion is very different from those of the other two presidents. He shows more positive attitude in his speech. While Roosevelt and Obama have relatively balanced speech and share similar emotion distribution. Trump is the one who has the least negative emotion in his speech. His chart is a combination of high trust and joy with a low sadness and disgust. That reflects the situation Trump is at the moment of the speech.
